0.body: Vex is an enforcer of local style guidelines, in the form of a hackable linter. Vex scans source files for non-idiomatic code-patterns expressed via a set of user-provided Starlark scripts. These scripts declare tree-sitter queries , reason about their results and create pretty, human-readable warnings which annotate source files. When working on any codebase---especially large ones---conventions naturally arise and although ultimately noble in intent, they all share a significant problem. Typical tools for code standardisation express preferences at the level of all code written in a particular language but conventions are most often at the level of specific code and hence no pattern gets enforced. Therefore, to ensure consistency, we must rely on fallible human review to identify and help eliminate non-standard code-patterns. Consistency is now at the mercy of human mistakes, hence inconsistency is inevitable. This need not be the way. Vex allows subjective style preferences to be defined at a level closer to the project, specifically through a folder of vexes in the project root. These are then mechanically enforced throughout the project, leaving no room for later ugly surprises. For truly excellent code, Vex is used alongside language-specific formatters and linters. This tool is perfect for anyone looking to improve the consistency and hence the quality of their or their team’s code. To get started, install Vex and then follow the let’s write a vex tutorial . The rest of these docs is organised as follows: Tutorials Hands-on lessons in vex-writing How-to guides Step-by-step instructions for common tasks Reference materials Technical information about vex Explanations Long-form discussion of key-topics
0.title: Introduction

1.body: Vex supports Linux, macOS and Windows. Assuming that cargo is installed, open a terminal and run the following--- cargo install --git https://github.com/TheSignPainter98/vex Test the installation by running vex. If vex appears unavailable, ensure that ~/.cargo/bin/ is present in your $PATH and then retry.
1.title: Installation

10.body:
Put the cursor at the end of vex script. If absent, copy the following function into the script--- def find_child(node, predicate): for child in node.children(): if predicate(child): return child match = find_child(child, predicate) if match != None: return match return None Move to where the matching child is required. Call the find_child function, passing the node whose children are to be searched and a function or lambda which takes a node returns whether it is the desired one. For example, to find the first child let_declaration node, use the following--- find_child( node_to_search, lambda node: node.kind == 'let_declaration',
)

10.title: How to search child nodes, returning the first match

11.body:
Put the cursor at the end of vex script. If absent, copy the following function into the script--- def find_all_children(node, predicate, allow_nested=False): def _find_children(node, predicate, allow_nested, ret) for child in node.children(): if predicate(child): ret.append(child) if not allow_nested: continue _find_children(child, predicate, allow_nested=allow_nested, ret=ret) ret = [] _find_children(node, predicate, allow_nested, ret) return ret Move to where the matching child is required. Call the find_all_children function, passing the node whose children are to be searched and a function or lambda which takes a node returns whether to include it in the output. For example, to find all child let_declaration nodes, use the following--- find_all_children( node_to_search, lambda node: node.kind == 'let_declaration', allow_nested=True,
)

14.body:
Put the cursor at the end of vex script. If absent, copy the following function into the script--- def find_all_parents(node, predicate, allow_nested=False): return [ parent for parent in node.parents() if predicate(parent) ] Move to where the matching child is required. Call the find_all_parents function, passing the node whose parents are to be searched and a function or lambda which takes a node returns whether to include it in the output. For example, to find all parent let_declaration nodes, use the following--- find_all_parents( node_to_search, lambda node: node.kind == 'let_declaration',
) The variable let_declarations is now a list.

16.body: Globs are patterns, commonly seen in shell language, used to represent one or multiple file paths. Vex supports the following glob features: [1] ? matches any single character. * matches any (possibly empty) sequence of characters. ** matches the current directory and arbitrary subdirectories. This sequence must form a single path component, so both **a and b** are invalid and will result in an error. A sequence of more than two consecutive * characters is also invalid. [...] matches any character inside the brackets. Character sequences can also specify ranges of characters, as ordered by Unicode, so e.g. [0-9] specifies any character between 0 and 9 inclusive. An unclosed bracket is invalid. [!...] is the negation of [...], i.e. it matches any characters not in the brackets. The metacharacters ?, *, [, ] can be matched by using brackets (e.g. [?]). When a ] occurs immediately following [ or [! then it is interpreted as being part of, rather then ending, the character set, so ] and NOT ] can be matched by []] and [!]] respectively. The - character can be specified inside a character sequence pattern by placing it at the start or the end, e.g. [abc-]. This list originally came from the Pattern docs in the excellent glob Rust crate , used by this project.

5.body: Open a terminal, type and run--- vex list languages Find the name of the desired language in the list. Open vex.toml. If absent, on a new line at the end of the file, type out a new section [<language-name>]. In this section, if absent, type out a new use-for = [] field. In the square brackets from the previous step, type a glob in double-quotes which matches the desired file.

5.title: How to override a file’s language

6.body: Open a terminal in the root directory of your project. Type and run--- vex init You should now see a new file, vex.toml, and a new directory, vexes/ containing an example vex.

7.body: In terminal, copy the vex ID to ignore (warning[<vex-id-here>]). Open the file containing the code which triggered the warning. Move the cursor to the start of that code. Type out a comment with the following text--- vex:ignore <vex-id-here>
